@Hunterese123 Infinity War and Endgame, as well as Civil War, were making use of pre-established characters. We watch their solo movies and knew what they were about. That is why those team up movies worked.

Movies like this, where it INTRODUCES a bunch of new characters simultaneously, are bad. Imagine if Marvel released Infinity War, but literally none of the other MCU movies existed. No Ironman, Captain America, Thor, Spiderman, Dr. Strange, Guardians of the Galaxy, etc. movies to give us context to those characters, their personalities, their motivations, their powers, etc.. If that happened, then Infinity War would be a mess, because it would just be a bunch of characters who we've never seen before and who we don't care about.

No, it doesn't matter that we already know who Superman is. We need a proper introduction to THIS specific Superman. Why do you think the MCU worked so well? Go back and watch the original Ironman, Captain America, etc. and ask yourself why they didn't make those movies big epic team up movies like Infinity War.

@lonewulv13it’s not that the other iterations haven’t saved people or stood up for them. They miss the point that he’s an optimistic farm boy from Kansas with a heart of Gold that wouldn’t hurt a fly if he could help it. What I’m saying is the way they represent him saving people & the relationship he has with the people of metropolis is what they get wrong! 

In Man of Steel, people look up to him as a God, or rather someone above them. As opposed this recent one, where they see him as a beacon of hope & care for him enough to pick him up when he falls

Edit: and by optimism he loves being human! He embraces it & still sees the beauty in humanity as opposed to MoS and BvS where he’s almost distant from humanity and only really gives a shit about lois

